<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-06-13T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-06-13T18:00:00-05:00" n="469" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d469">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.941/13197: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-06-13T19:00:00-04:00">June 13, 1938—7
                                p.m.</date></dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>176. Your 286, June 12, 1 p.m.,<note n="59" xml:id="d469fn59"><ref target="frus1931-41v01#pg_600"><hi rend="italic">Foreign
                                        Relations</hi>, Japan, 1931–1941, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 600</ref>.</note> and previous telegrams in
                            regard to Japanese notice of the imminent extension of hostilities into
                            the river area between Wuhu and Hukow. Please warn Americans residing in
                            that area and, if you consider it advisable, in the Kiukiang–Nanchang
                            area, of the danger and repeat to them advice that they withdraw by the
                            most practicable routes to places of safety.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
